# JavaScript & TypeScript

Apply these rules to every JS/TS change in this project.

## Use ES14 (ES2024)

- ES modules (`import`/`export`), `const`/`let`, `async`/`await`
- Optional chaining (`?.`), nullish coalescing (`??`), `Object.hasOwn()`
- Prefer `Object.groupBy()`, `Promise.withResolvers()`, non-mutating `Array.toSorted()` / `with()`
- Private class fields (`#field`), `structuredClone()`, `import type` for types
- No `var`, `require`, `any`, or legacy callback patterns

## KISS

- Simplest correct solution; one purpose per function, method, or class
- No abstractions until a pattern repeats; no speculative error handling
- Match surrounding conventions; minimal diffs; comments only for non-obvious logic

## Favor OOP

- **Entities** — classes with factory methods and domain behavior (`canBeViewedBy`, `toJSON`)
- **Services** — constructor-injected dependencies; orchestrate use cases
- **Repositories** — encapsulate data access
- **Handlers** — thin; delegate to services (no inline business logic)
- **React UI** — functional components; extract stateful logic into classes/modules when warranted

```typescript
// ✅ Service class with injection
export class ReportService {
  constructor(private readonly repo: ServiceReportRepository) {}
  async createReport(input: CreateReportInput) { /* ... */ }
}

// ❌ Procedural handler with embedded rules
export const handler = async (e) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(e.body);
  return { statusCode: 200, body: JSON.stringify(data.filter(/* rules */)) };
};
```
